  "text": "Capturing the pro le of the utility network based on the vectorisation of echograms on rectilinear segments has yielded very good accuracy results. However, this is a multi-stage and time-consuming process. The longer the length of the utility line, the greater the e ort required to perform repetitive activities, that is, analysis and vectorisation of subsequent echograms -B-scan. Only after the data has been processed for the entire segment, is it possible to perform the approximation of the axis pro le. According to the authors of this publication, for the needs of the GESUT database, this process can be replaced by the vectorisation of the pro le of the utilities identi able on the horizontal slices of the C-scan of the 3D model performed at the appropriate depths (Fig. 13) . The quality of 2D data processing into a three-dimensional model depends largely on the selected interpolation parameters [CITATION_1] and the adopted coordinate system. There are two main ways of positioning echograms in space. The processes and problems described here are adequate for the ReexW software, in which the processing has been carried out. The rst method involves the creation of a 3D model in a local system, for which the point of origin and the X axis are determined by the rst pro le of the model. The origins of subsequent echograms are arranged in accordance with the assumed pro ling step along the Y axis. The interpolation is performed along the axis of the adopted system. This method is most e ective in the event of the maximum ful lment of conditions such as: the parallelism and equidistant increment of the subsequent pro les, the measurement step and the number of traces in the pro le. The interpolated data lls tightly and closes within the boundaries of the studied area (Fig. 13) .",
